<font color="#FF0000">WAKING UP</font><br>
<tt>Mon Aug  4 12:39:29 US/Eastern 1997
</tt><p>
I agree that love and relationships shouldn't be about control and dependency but rather mutual respect, supportiveness and honesty.  People here have said that they have been in bad relationships when all of a sudden they &quot;woke up&quot; and realized that their partner wasn't treating them right.  I'm still curious to know what it takes for people to &quot;wake up&quot; to the disappointing reality that the relationship you're in is holding you back from fully expressing yourself in the world on your own terms.<br><br>
It can be hard to walk away from bad relationships for a lot of different reasons.  Sometimes the person uses fear or intimidation to continue a cycle of control.  Other times it's scary and painful to leave someone who could make you feel so good about yourself at times.  Also, I think that if people have experienced patterns of pain, control or abuse in their relationships with family members, they can end up choosing partners who treat them the same way that their family members did. People can expect love to be painful because that's all they've known in their past relationships.<br><br>
I remember my first relationship from when I was in high school.  I knew things weren't working out but it was really difficult for me to think about breaking up with my boyfriend because it was so satisfying to have somebody really like me and notice me for the first time.  I wondered when that would ever happen to me again.  Fortunately, things did come to an end but it was really hard for me to trust people after that experience.  I didn't want to put myself in another situation where someone else could hurt me like that.   At the same time I think that always keeping yourself safe from having to potentially feel pain is almost like not really living at all.  Sometimes you do have to take risks so that you can grow and learn from your experiences.<br>

